\begin_layout Subsubsection
Fourier discretization in r-direction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Without at least carefully-chosen levels of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

-diffusion,
 the instability tends to grow at the grid scale in the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

-direction on a finite element grid,
 which might mean that growth rates,
 etc.
 are significantly affected by numerical errors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To run without 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

-diffusion and without numerical error for a single 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|k_{r}\right|$
\end_inset

,
 we could instead use a Fourier 
\begin_inset Quotes els
\end_inset

pseudospectral
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

 discretisation for the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 dimension,
 where we keep 3 distinct spatial grid points,
 so that when we Fourier-transform there is only the constant-in-
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 component and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm k_{r}$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{r}$
\end_inset

 being set by the radial size of the box 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{r}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a bonus,
 this makes simulations cheaper,
 as there are only 3 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

-grid points,
 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{element}}n_{\mathrm{grid}}\sim64$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

-grid points on a typical finite element grid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any nonlinearities that physically would couple different non-zero 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{r}$
\end_inset

 are missing,
 but we only want to look at the linear phase of the mode here,
 so that should be OK.
\end_layout

